January Sunday 30, 1927

Went to El Monte for a family picnic with Youngs, Werts, Spencers, Cronans. Start at 11:30 back at 5:30. A clear warm day. Hunted before lunch in the rocks on the hillside to the south of the picnic grounds. Got one X.H. and one bat. Another lizard seen by Spencer; could not check. After lunch walked across the river. No frogs seen, nor pollywogs. Nothing seen on the road. Miles 56.

1927 Saturday 26, February

Went for a ride with Philip at 1:30; returned at 4:30. 54 Miles. A dull sunless day. To Tia Juana, Bonita, Sweetwater Dam and Lemon Grove. Saw plenty toads run over in the road but no snakes. Detienne had said he saw 3 in the Tia Juana Valley after the flood but I couldn't find any.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/26/2014 04:23 PM
  • cassieswindle 05/09/2011 12:23 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

February Sunday 27, 1927

Went to Morena (north of Old Town) at 3 P.M. Returned at 4:30. A good sunny day. Walked about a mile along the Santa Fe R. of W. Overturning ties boards etc. Got 1 batrachoseps. Saw plenty pollywogs in one pond. Also saw one lizard; probably medium alligator. Got one large ring-neck under a tin sign; was coiled up.

60 - March Tuesday 1, 1927

Went to Rotary Club in Escondido for lunch with Tom Bridges. Start at 10:45; back at 3:15. A fine clear warm day. 64 miles.

Got one garter at Poway. Had been run over but was still alive and ok for a specimen. Also saw something looked like a dead snake on Poway grade but couldn't stop.

65 - 1927 Sunday 6, March

Went to the north foot of Poway Grade. Started at 2:30; returned at 6 P.M. 35 miles. A clear warm day. Got 2 b.a. on 5th St opposite AEK's flat. Picked up AEK. Got 2 b.a. under stones at foot of Poway Grade, north side. Got one small Uta under a board at Miramar junction. No snakes seen alive or dead.

Philip caught an alligator lizard

75 - 1927 Wednesday 16, March

Heard today of many snakes being seen lately so after lunch went out to Flynn Springs via Lakeside returning via Bostonia. Start 1:30; return 4:15. 54 miles. A clear warm day after a week of fine weather. Saw nothing alive or dead.

Miss Arnold brought in 7 B.A. today. Some very small. Last week 6.

78 - March Saturday 19, 1927

A fine warm clear day. Rather dry. Went to Ramona and return with Philip. Start at 1:30 return at 5:30 miles 77. Went via Bostonia and Lakeside. Returned via Lakeside - Lakeview.
No snakes seen on the road alive or dead.

One squashed Alligator Lizard on the road at Footer.

Stopped at top of grade just north of where Wildwood road branches and hunted in the rocks about 1 hour.

Got one x.h. one large skink and one large Hypsiglena. Saw several more x.h. but lost them. Saw one Orcutti. Very few lizards running about. Saw only one other - couldn't tell what it was.

The skink was under a stone resting on the ground.

The spotted night snake was under a rock resting on another rock - flat on top.

Page Edit History:

79 - 1927 Sunday 20, March

A fine warm clear day although a little chilly and windy beyond Pine Valley. 170 miles.

Went to top of Mountain Springs Grade with family and Leas. Stopped for lunch between Pine Valley and Buckmans.

Start at Noon; returned at 6:30

Did no hunting. No live snakes or lizards seen on the road.

Saw what may have been a dead snake near Flynn Springs but did not stop.

83 - 1927 Thursday 24, March

Went to La Jolla to take gg out. Good clear day. 30 miles 3:30 to 6:00 P.M.

1 dead gopher snake large on the road at Rose Canyon branch.

84 - March Friday 25, 1927

Went to La Jolla in the afternoon. A cloudy day. Saw nothing. miles 28

Page Edit History:

85 - 1927 Saturday 26, March

Went to La Jolla in the morning. A clearing day. Saw nothing. miles 28

In the afternoon went to Dulzura summit with Hugo and Ed. Clear and warm. Start at 2 P.M.; return at 6:30. Miles 68.

Saw no snakes on the road alive or dead. Saw one small lizard and probably one horned toad.

Hunted at Dulzura Summit. Got 8 Xantusias and lost several more. Were under flakes as usual.

Got one medium C. exsul. Was under a flat rock exposed to sun. Could be seen from the side. No fight.

Got one large red C. mitchelli. Was coiled in the usual place under a large rock with a hollow underneath. Retreated inside at once. Could be seen from the side. Hard to get but finally landed him.

On the road saw 2 lizards; one was probably a horned toad. Only one or two (besides x.h.) in the rocks. One was an Orcutti

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/26/2014 04:52 PM
  • SVielma 01/24/2014 12:14 PM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

86 - March Sunday 27, 1927

A part cloudy day. Little sunshine where we hunted. Too cold for snakes.

Went to County Line at Rainbow with family & Harriett C. Start at 9:45 returned at 6:10. Went via Oceanside; returned via Camp Kearney and La Jolla. Total miles 157.

Saw no live snakes. One dead garter snake (T. sirtalis infernalis?) on the road (east side) about 1/2 mile north of Bonsall. Saved specimen.

Hunted in the rocks about 1/2 mile north of Rainbow. Hunted diligently but got nothing. Saw a couple of skellies and another unidentified lizard. Rocks not good quality to flake; some hard some soft. Saw no Xantusias.

A poor day (except for the surprising garter snake) owing principally to coolness and lack of sunshine. The virtual absence of snakes in the road indicates that they are not traveling much as yet but they should be out in the roads.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/26/2014 04:54 PM

89 - 1927 Wedneday 30, March

(Sunday April 24th Continued)
Coming back Callisaurus was plentiful to a point 1/2 way bet Narrows and Yaqui Well.

On the return trip the following snakes were checked.
1 small Calif King D.O.R Santa Ysabel.
1 large Banded Racer D.O.R. on grade between Ballena and Ramona.
1 large Banded Racer about 4 miles east of Ramona
1 large Calif King about 4 miles east of Ramona

The Calif King had swallowed the racer and then had been run over. About 3 inches of the tail was protruding.

1 large Banded Racer 2 mi east of Ramona D.O.R
1 large Calif King caught crossing the road at Ramona.
1 small Gopher D.O.R. Ramona
1 small Pacific Rattler D.O.R. Fosters

On the whole a successful lizard trip but not snakes. Reason: not enough time spent west of the mountains hunting snakes; and too hot east.

1 Callisaurus with red mites.

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/26/2014 04:57 PM
  • AMS 03/06/2014 01:55 AM
  • SVielma 01/25/2014 05:27 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

90 - March Thursday 31, 1927

(Sunday April 24th continued 2)

Altogether from Yaqui Well out and back we got:

29 Callisaurus

1 Leopard

5 Utas

5 Whiptails

5 Dipsosaurus

In addition got a number of specimens of each which were in such poor shape that they were not saved. Lost tails and shot up.

On the way home stopped in the Sentenac Well up toward the top and hunted an hour or so. Got 2 Collared lizards,
3 Utas
2 Orcuttis

Also saw the Mearnsi and Chuckawallas but got none.

Got an alligator D.O.R. at Julian which saved. Stopped for a short time on the grade between Ramona and Ballena and got an Orcutti and a S.o.b. saw Utas. Rocks here are of poor quality.

(Turn to March 30)

Page Edit History:
  • lwilliams 09/29/2014 01:14 PM
  • lwilliams 09/29/2014 01:14 PM

91 - 1927 Friday 1, April

(Sunday April 24 Continued)

did not range so far. Found Callisaurus to be most plentiful. Nearly always perched on the small rocks on the side of the road where Uta had been earlier in the morning and further back. Quite easy to get a good series of Callisaurus. Also an occasional Dipsosaurus was perched in this way. Callisaurus often standing high up to avoid heat.

In general it may be said that Utas are seen on the road particularly from the foot of the Sentenac to the Narrows; far beyond.

Leopards seem to be rare. Got only 1 this near the Narrows.

Whiptails are quite common 2 or 3 miles east of the Narrows. Seem to like the semi-rocky areas.

Callisaurus most common of all.

Dipsosaurus in the shade of the bushes around Borega hotel. Got 5 here.

The Borega hotel keeper says "Diamond Backs", Sidewinders and Gophers are plentiful around the hotel. But are found only in the evening and at night. No frogs.

(Continued on Mar 30)

92 April Saturday 2, 1927

Went to matinee.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 02/16/2014 06:30 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

93 - 1927 Sunday 3, April

Went on a botanizing trip. Start at 8 a.m. - Return at 7:30 P.M. with Abbott, Fleming, Gordon, Kraekel, McEwen, C.F. Brooks, Dr & Mrs. Clemens. Went to El Cajon, Hillsdale, Monte Vista Ranch, Jamul, Lyons Valley, Barrett, Cottonwood, half way up Portrero grade, thence home via Jamul and highway.

Notes.

Saw only one dead snake this being a small gopher in the park on Pershing Drive. Saw no live snakes.

Got a chance to hunt in the rocks only at one place; this being at Jamul. Here got 3 x.h. Had been burned over last year but only one was found in rocks that had been burned. Saw several others.

A few other lizards were out but not many.

Got stuck in the mud in Lyons Valley; also caught in soft new road on Barrett-Cottonwood road. Hard work to get out.

Day was warm but part cloudy. Rain during the week.

1 dead garter snake East San Diego
1 dead striped racer on highway opposite Chollas Hts Wireless.

97 - Thursday 7, April

Next hunted in the rocks east of the road on the Mussey Grade a little north of Shady Dell. Spent about half an hour here. Got several x.h. bringing the total for the day to 10. Also got a medium skink under a rock with a bright pink tail.

Then under a good sized rock Weiss found a large Trimorphodon the largest I have had yet. As usual was under a heavy rock, not a flake. Got him almost uninjured except for a couple of minor scratches. The time was about 5 P.M. Rather dark. Buzzed his tail when caught.

98 - April Friday 8, 1927

Went to Gas Co Camp in Goose Valley to see progress of work on the Sutherland dam line. With Weiss. Start at 10 AM Return at 6:30. Miles 94. A part cloudy day. Some clear spells. Too cool for a good snake day. Practically no lizards seen about.

Dead snakes 1 Pacific medium on the highway about a mile above Foster's.

1 Boyle's King large on the University extension opposite the Wireless station.

First stopped for lunch at the camp in Goose Valley, thence to Sutherland dam site. Here hunted in the rocks for a few moments only. Got a Uta stansburiana alive. On the way back stopped on the grade a mile or so toward Ramona from the concrete bridge. At this point got 3 x.h.

Next stopped at the highest point on the grade and went up to the peak to the west; the large boulders looked good but proved to have few flakes. Hunted here strenuously for nearly two hours. Got a few x.h.; 2 orcuttis and a medium boa. The latter was extended full length but was not moving when first seen

100 - April Sunday 10, 1927

A cold rainy day. Did not go out. Busy preparing a snake talk which was delivered at the Natural History Society in the afternoon.

Garder showed me a young C.c. mormon taken in Mission Valley. Showed the body blotches very distinctly.

From the Zoo got an unusually large T.o. hammondii. Caught 4-10-27 at Chula Vista by Verne Mirrifield. Measured 37 1/8" long. Contained a large toad which measured 8" long. Snake was a female and contained many eggs.

106 - April Saturday 16, 1927

A cold windy cloudy day with patches of sunshine. Rain in the back country yesterday.

Went to the Earl School with HK. Start at 1:45 Return at 5:30. 69 miles.

Only one snake seen alive or dead this being a dead garter on the highway at Pepper Drive. Large.

First hunted in the rocks east of the road near Shady Dell. Got 3 x.h., 1 Uta, 1 Skelly. All were in cracks in the rocks; none running about. Saw an orcutti and several other x.h. Got 2 Hyla arenicolor in cracks in the rocks. Found a small xantusia that had choked to death on a grub which was stuck in his throat.

Hunted for a short time in the rocks beyond Earl School. Got nothing. These rocks look good from the road but are of poor quality without flakes.

A poor day. Too cold and damp for snakes.

107 - 1927 Sunday 17, April

Went to Coyote Wells with family and famous meteorologist Dr. C.F. Brooks. Start at 9:15; return at 7:15 P.M. 197 miles. Clear in town; cloudy in the mountains (and cold and windy). Part cloudy and comfortable in the desert. Went out by the highway; returned by Campo.

While this was a fairly good day it was rather too cold in the mountains for snakes and too soon after cold and rainy weather. It had recently rained hard at a number of points last night.

Only one snake was seen; a dead gopher half grown at Dulzura.

First stop at the top of new Viejas grade. Some fairly good flakes here. Got X.h. and one young S. orcutti. Next stop was at crest beyond La Posta. Got one Uta here under a rock. Cold and partly dormant.

Stopped for lunch at foot of Mt. Springs grade on the edge of the rocky hills. Some fairly good flakes here. Got 2 Phyllodactylus tuberculosus under level flakes also lost one. They are probably quite common here. Also saw several Uta.

Notes:

AMS

fort? of int? springs

108 - April Monday 18, 1927

Sunday April 17 Cont

mearnsi and one Uta stansburiana. Did not see any x.h. Hunted here about an hour. Left my best pistol on spare tires and so lost it. Got a bat.

Went into Coyote Wells. Did not see any lizards of any kind running on the desert although it was about 74°F. Stopped only at one point to pick ocotillo and saw nothing here.

The geckos squeak. They are both infected with the vermillion mites. Examined under the microscope they are 8 legged rather hairy. They held a piece of skin in their jaws when removed.


Monday April 18

Found a yearling gopher dead on Maple Street.

A very cold day.

110 - April Wednesday 20, 1927

Went to Sutherland Dam and San Pasqual to see lines under construction. With Ayres, Peckham, Lawrie. Start 8:45 AM; returned at 6 P.M. 111 miles. Went via Highway and Ramona; returned via San Pasqual and Escondido.

This was the first real snake day of the year. Clear and warm; little wind.

Kelly gave us a large gopher which he had picked up at Earl School. Later this died.

Stopped at Ramona for a few moments; then went to the dam. Stopped here a short time. Saw one Uta.

Came back to rocks about one mile north of the upper end of Goose Valley. Hunted here 3/4 hour. Got four x.h. and one Hyla arenicolor. Saw skellys, utas and orcuttis. Lost my pistol but luckily Lawrie found it. The rocks were not of extra good quality.

There were many lizards on the road between Sutherland and the camp. First time this year I have seen many. Lost a horned toad at Ramona.

Went down the Clevinger grade and hunted for about an hour and a half in the rocks and cactiis on the north side of the road about a mile east of the battle field. Got a Trimorphodon,

111 - 1927 Thursday 21, April


a boa and a small worm snake. Also a Colyonyx and a Xantusia. Saw Utas, Orcuttis and Skullys. The rocks here are not of good quality. Few flakes.

The Trimorphodon was under a large cap rock level and closely fitting. The boa was in a crack in the rocks and was fished out with difficulty. The Coleonyx was under a cap rock. The worm snake was under a thick flake touching the ground under a large rock about 10 feet away bust was lost.

On the way into Escondido got a yearling gopher crossing the road; the only snake seen on the road this day.

Got a large Calif. King and a small red rattler from Kemp the truck driver. Both from San Pasqual.

113 - 1927 Saturday 23, April

Went to Ramona Camp with Stearns, Fowler, Holloway, Savage, Peckham, Weiss, Ayres, Foster and 3 kids. Started at 1:30. Went out by way of Helix and Grossmont.

A clear hot day; 4th of a series. Quite hot in the back country. Miles 46.

Got a juvenile gopher crossing the road just above Helix store. Found a dead garter on the road one mile south of Fosters.

First stop between the school near Gregg's place and the foot of Mussey. Went up in the rocks north of the road and hunted here nearly an hour. Saw several X.h. and Uta. Got 1 X.h. and a fine Coleonyx under a rock cap.

One dead Racer on the road just n.e. of this point. Call it Mussey's.

Next stop on Mussey's just opposite the big rock. Did not hunt here as Fowler and Ayres had been over and reported nothing.

Next stop at the rocks on the east side of the road about a mile above Shady Dell. Just across the creek got a medium Pacific. Was stretched out in the oak leaves.

Then worked hard in the rocks for an hour and a half but got nothing except 1 Uta (not saved). The rocks were of poor consistency; too hard.

114 - April Sunday 24, 1927

Got up this A.M. at 4:45 and started with same party at 5:45 for Borega Valley. Reached Borega at noon. Returned to San Diego (via Helix) at 7:15 P.M. Another hot day; 102 in the shade at Borega. Miles today 162. Found the roads better than previous trip except Banner and Sentenac grades which have been washed.

In the morning up to the time we reached the Narrows few lizards were seen. There were a few Utas perched on the side rocks of which we got 3 between Yaqui Well and the Narrows. Stopped at the Narrows for the first hunt but found lizards scarce. Washed away by flood? Got one Leopard Lizard and a Callisaurus.

Dead snakes on the way out were as follows:
1 Spotted Night 1/2 way bet Ramona and Ballena (on the grade)
1 Spotted Night near Wynola (about 2 mi west)
1 Juvenile Gopher at Wynola
1 Juvenile Gopher at Pine Hills Junction

On the long straight run from the Narrows to Borega Hotel we stopped occasionally to hunt or to shoot individual lizards. On the return trip we stopped for more individuals but (continued under Friday April 1)

120 - April Saturday 30, 1027

Started for Borega at 10:30 with Slevin, Toze, H.K., Weiss, Chuck, Talbott, Bill. Clear but cooler than last week.

Lunched at Goose Valley Camp. Stopped for a few minutes in the rocks near camp. Got a Uta and a Skelly. Next stop just of Sentenac. Got 4 Utas.

Stopped one or two places between Narrows and Borega. Got 2 or 3 Utas and a Phrynosoma platyrhinos. Has orange lice. Examined some. Seemed to have six legs. Also before this trip was over found them on Callisaurus, Dipsosaurus, Crotaphytus.

Arrive at hotel at 5:30. Was cooler bet Narrows and Hotel than last week. Not a single Callisaurus was seen; because cooler or afternoon?

After supper walked around setting traps. Got 3 Sonora Occipitalis. Drove to County line. Got nothing. While down there hotel man got a sidewinder.

Hunted again for Sonoras but got none. Slevin saw a Colyonyx. Turned in at 11 P.M.

Miles 102 + 5 = 107

121 - 1927 Sunday 1, May

Today begins hot but by afternoon became somewhat hazy and a little cooler.

Went out at 5:30 AM to rocky hills to the north west. Looked good but got nothing. Saw several whiptails on return.

With all members of the party drove about 5 miles toward the Narrows. Stopped a number of places and hunted. Got many lizards, Utas, Whips, Calls, Dips, 1 Crota. Piece of snake skin.

The Callisaurus are by far the most numerous. Seem to like best the areas where small round boulders are scattered. Run with tails over backs and stop suddenly which tends to conceal them. Next Utas then Whips. Whips seem to like rocky ground. Crotaphytus rarest. Got one more horned toad.

There are certainly plenty of lizards in this area.

Returned to hotel for lunch, then started for town at 1:45.

Did not stop often going in (continued Friday, April 29)

134 - May Saturday 14, 1927

A poor day - too hot.

135 - 1927 Sunday 15, May

A somewhat cooler day than yesterday. Started at 7 AM for La Puerta where we arrived at 10:30. Left Slevin's equipment and went on down to Vallecito. Returned to La Puerta at 1 P.M. Left at 1:50 and arrived in San Diego at 5:45. Miles 136.

Only one snake seen on the entire tip. 1 Long nose D.O.R. at Gregg's Bridge - San Vicente. Too hot today for snakes.

In the Borega Valley saw plenty of Utas and Callys. Also a couple of Whiptails.

Toze got a large Dipsosaurus. We got one horned toad (Platyrhinos). 1/2 way bet Yaqui Well and foot of Sentenac got 2 large S. magister. Fine specimens. Take refuge in trees.

Between La Puerta and Vallecito got a couple of Collard Lizards. Saw Calllys in La Puerta Valley + Vallecito Valley.

Saw mountain quail with young in Sentenac and at Vallecito.

At Vellecito got plento of Hyla regilla and B.b. halophilus. Also saw polywogs.

Got a Crotaphylus in Sentenac Cañon.

Stephens gave Slevin a large Chuck taken the day before in Box Cañon.

141 - 1927 Saturday 21, May

Went to La Puerta to get Slevin. Started at 10:10. A cold day cloudy in town; cold and windy in the back country altho clear. At Julian it was too cold for comfort. Cool and windy in La Puerta. Slevin reported it too cold for best results during his stay.

Went out with L.B. Jones. Itinerary Lakeside, Ramona, Julian, La Puerta back through Julian thence Santa back Ysabel, Warner's Dam, Rencin, Pala, Ronsse's Camp. Total miles 174. Camp at 6:30.

Did no hunting on this trip except in the evening when we spend a short time in the San Luis Rey river bed and got a Hyla and a Toad. Heard a peculiar triller call which Slevin thought might be d Bufo Punctatus.

Got a medium horned toad at Ramona.
Dead snakes this trip. Not a live snake seen.
1 Large gopher N end Lakeside bridge 22 mi

143 - 1927 Monday 23, May


Sunday 22nd Continued
but got nothing. Rocks of poor quality as usual. Stopped at Silvano. Saw x.h. but got nothing. Lost a horned toad a little further on.

Next lunched at the San Pasqual Battlefield and then hunted in the rocks and cactus about the field. Got 1 x.h. saw verticaria orcuttii.

Caught a glimpse of the racer in the brush and burned cactus. Looked for him and as usual saw him watching us a few feet away with his head raised 6 in out of the bush. Had to shoot him.

Couldn't stop. Hot at Needles. Few lizards seen. This section of mojave desert more sprinkled with Mts. than Colo. desert. Arrived at 8:30; 382 mi.

145 - 1927 Wednesday 25, May

Lizards are extremely plentiful on the rocks along the roadside. Saw whiptails, utas, callys, both crotaphytus, dipsosairus. Count get any number here. Then a little later approaching Oatman saw nay large chucks. Could get any number with shotgun.

156 - June Sunday 5, 1927

Today went to Camp, Buckmans, Pine Valley, Julian, Ramona and home. Start at 8:30 Returned at 7:15. 164 miles. With Philip, Hugo, Slevin. A fine day high fog in town clear in the back country. Little wind. Not overly warm.

First stopped at Dulzura and hunted from about 9:30 to 11:30. Got only 5 x.h., 1 Uta. Saw a number of Orcuttis but got no snakes not withstanding hard work. One x.h. badly infested with red mites. Going up the Potrero grade a Leopard Lizard near the Tecate Junction. Lunched south of Buckmans. Here saw a whiptail. Hunted for a while at Shady Dell but got nothing. Saw 1 X.h. Also first A. Lugubris from San Diego County.

---1 Rhinocheilus Chollas Hts. Large.
This snake was crossing the highway as we came up. Was making poor progress % smoothness of surface. Was in middle of highway. We stopped to pick it up, but before we could reach it at least 4 cars had run over it so it could not be used as a specimen. Was good illustration of how snakes get run over.

163 - 1927 Sunday 12, June

Quite a heavy rain last night and this morning. Had expected to have a picnic lunch in the back country but gave it up.

At 8:30 went to San Diego River bridge at Old TOwn with Phil and Henry Schnell. Back at 10:00. Got 2 Hylas, 9 Scaphiopus hammondii and about 100 Bufo. b. halophilus. There were many there but rather difficult to catch in the tall high grass very wet. Pickled 20 bufo and the rest.

In the afternoon at 2 P.M. went to the country with Phil. It was still cold and cloudy in town but in the back country was clear and comfortable. Had evidently rained some withing the past 2 days. Went to Descanso, Cuyamaca, Julian, Ramona. Returned at 7 P.M. Hunted only at one point; top of new Viejas grade. Got 1 x.h.; saw several also Orcuttis.

180 - June Wednesday 29, 1927

Started out this morning at 7 AM. A fine clear cool day except somewhat hot in the vicinity of Pala. The fact that so few snakes were seen proves that tho tapering off in the catch at this time is not due to the weather. Traveled via Julian, Pine Hills, Santa Ysabel, Henshaw Dam, Palomar, Pala, Bonsall, Oceanside and Home. Reached office at 4:30. Left Chickering at Oceanside, Fleming at Torrey Pines. 137 miles. 183 - 1927 Saturday 2, July

Started for Pine Valley alone at 1 P.M. Arrived at 3 P.M. Went via Encanto and cut off to Orange Ave El Cajon. 51 miles. A moderately cool day.

1 med Gopher DOR beyond Alpine Hospital.

Went out before supper to the bridge and after supper around the camp with flash lamps but got nothing.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/07/2014 05:03 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

184 - July Sunday 3, 1927

In the afternoon drove to Clover Flat via White Eagle with Phil. At Clover Flat got many B.b. halophilus from very small to larage juvenile, few small B.c. Californicus and few Hyla regilla

At Cottonwood got

Many Bbh

Many Bcc

Many Hyla reg.

Few Hyla aren.

There were a few unmorphored poly wogs in the pond, probably B.c.c. as many of latter were very small.

Noted a whiptail at Clover Flat.

Walked across the valley in the evening nd heard the Bcc trill also H.r. and H.a. but caught nothing total miles 49. No snakes seen alive or dead.

Wether comfortable.

Notes:

SVielma

unmorphored ??

185 - 1927 Monday 4, July

In the morning the kids brought in 4 small garters from Pine Creek. In the afternoon went along pools across the vally and caught 10 more garters. A little later kids caught a gopher In the evening went out with Phil. Across the valley and caught a B.c.c large and 3 medium. Heard the trill again but could not follow up. Also H.r and H.a.

weather comfortable.

191 1927 Sunday 10, July

Went to Cortemadera twice and Guatay once. 29 miles. No snakes on the road and no lizards. Rather hot.

Hunted frogs on the bank of the lake at Cortemadera but saw nothing.

In the creek between Crt. and Pine Valley got 10 small Hyla regilla and 1 small Hyla arenicolor

Saw one medium garter in the creek but lost him.

In the evening went out along pine creek to locate the trillers. Heard them again but could not locate. Got 1 Hyla regilla and 1 Hyla arenicolor. Former was croaking.

197 - 1927 Saturday 16, July

Started for Pine Valley at 1:30 P.M. arriving at 3:30. Alone. A hot day. Went via El Cajon Ave. miles 47.

Only one snake seen this trip.
1 Long nose at Flynn Springs DOR.

In the evening went out for a walk where the fire had been across the valley. Got 1 large Bufo boreas halophilus.

Also Philip gave me a Calif. King med he had caught at Cuyamaca (north end of the lake) and a Hyla regilla from Pine Valley.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/07/2014 06:58 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

198 - July Sunday 17, 1927

A hot day started out with family at 9:00 for Rattlesnake (Harper's Valley) went to Desert View not knowing the road and then came back to north end of Cuyamaca lake and found road. Went to Harper's for lunch.

Hunted along the creek. Saw stellys, Utas and Hylas. Caught 3 of the latter in the grass. Returned to Pine Valley at 3:30. No snakes seen. Total miles 61.

Started at 5 P.M. for Cottonwood Pond with kids and Colton kids. Returned at 7 P.M. miles 19. Hunted at Pond for about 1 1/2 hrs. Released one Buzzard caught in 2 traps.

Found 3 Rands in a side pond and caught 2. Very few Bufo boreas hal (young) in sight but got a few. Quite a few Hyla arenicolor some apparently full grown. Some were quite a ways up the canyon in dry ground. Many Bufo cognatus calif. of all small sizes. The largest were more plentiful in dry ground along sides of canyon. Caught 1 medium size (about 1 1/2" long) at dusk. Large small are scarcer than very small.

Caught one small alligator on the side of a rock (hunting?) at dusk and saw a whiptail.

The B.c.c are quite hard to catch in brush

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/07/2014 07:11 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

211 - 1927 Saturday 30, July

Pickled the 4 Ensatinas from Julian today.

The two largest measured as follows.

Total length 5 3/8" tail 2 1/4"

do do do do 2 3/8"

There were 14 eggs in the bunch. They adhere together. Yellowish and opaque. Practically round. Diam 5/16"

Recd from Abbott today 2 Garters caught by Huey from Laguna Hanson.

Measurded 4 Cal. striped racer eggs (lateralis) deposited in captivity about July 28

2 5/16 x 5/8

2 x 11/16

2 1/32 x 11/16

2 3/16 x 5/8

Notes:

220 - August Monday 8, 1927

Took venom today from 17 snakes. Got hooked in the left thumb by one fang of a C. exsul. more of a slash than a puncture. Felt pain instantly. Put on tourniquet. Sucked wound. Then used about 6 c.c. of antivenin. Not much pain. Evidently got very little.

This evening thumb slightly numb. Arm quite sore where antivenin injected.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/08/2014 03:43 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

299 - 1927 Wednesday 26, October

  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

300 - October Thursday 27, 1927

Rainy today; the first real rain of the season.

Tonight Philip and I went out on El Cajon Avenue where a toad migration had been reported in the Union as occurring the night before. Started at 6:45 and returned at 8:05. Was raining quite hard at times.

Many toads were observed crossing El Cajon and many were seen to be run over. We stopped at several points between 32nd and Euclid and picked up toads along the curb. In about 30 minutes of actual collecting we got

36 Bylo boreas halophilus

7 Scaphiopus hammondii

and 4 Large Hyla Regilla

No small toads were seen.

Best toad hunting I ever saw.

Miss Arnold Brought me 1 S.ham. this AM.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/08/2014 06:03 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

301 - 1927 Friday 28, October

Went out along El Cajon Avenue at noon but saw no live toads. Fewer smashed toads than I expected; they must have been washed away last night.

Went out at 7 P.M. to same location tonight. A clear dry night. Only 1 toad caught. It evidently must be actually raining to bring them out.

Page Edit History:
  • SVielma 03/08/2014 06:07 AM
  • psully 11/23/2010 01:39 PM

304 - October Monday 31, 1927

Went out on El Cajon Ave tonight with Phil. about 2 hours. Rained all day but was light tonight. Stopped before we came back.

Got 15 spade foots, 4 Hyla regilla; about 15 B.b. halophilus.

The spade foots croak in the jar. The Bufos twitter.

Toads (Bufo) distinctly less plentiful the first night.

352 - December Sunday 18, 1927

Drove out to Witch Creek and back with do Amaral. Nothing seen. A clear cool day; snow in the mountains. miles.

Do Amaral left for San Francisco on the two o'clock train.

This afternoon found eggs of Batrachoseps attenuatus? under a barel in the garden.

Turned out to be slug eggs (1-20-28)

L.g. boylii refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a ringed pattern.

L.g. californiae refers to the subspecies of king snake which has a striped pattern.
